Exercise 2

Plots the data in the dino dataset:

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")
ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Calculate the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

Exercise 3

Plots the data in the star dataset:

star_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "star")
ggplot(data = star_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Evaluate the correlation coefficient between x and y for the star dataset:

star_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0630

The star dataset compares to the dino dataset by being larger in size. However, they are very similar. The star data set correlation coefficient is -0.0629611, while the dino data set correlation coefficient is -0.06447185, which is just slightly smaller.

Exercise 5

Plot all datasets at once:

ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset))+
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(~ dataset, ncol = 3) + # facet the dataset variable, in 3 cols
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Calculate all of the datasets summary correlation coefficients:

datasaurus_dozen %>%
group_by(dataset) %>%
summarize(r = cor(x, y)) %>%
print(13)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
